			<blockquote style="border-left:3px solid var(--color-accent); padding-left:1rem; margin:0 0 2rem 0; font-style:italic; opacity:0.9;">
			"I didn't realize how much time we were losing until it came back. In the first month after go-live, I billed 14 additional hours that I would have spent on intake paperwork and follow-up emails."
			<footer style="margin-top:0.5rem; font-style:normal; font-size:0.85rem; opacity:0.7;">— Hypothetical managing partner, 9-attorney litigation firm</footer>
			</blockquote>

			<h4 class="accent-subtitle">The Challenge</h4>
			<p style="margin-bottom:1rem;">The firm's intake process hadn't changed in eight years. A prospective client would fill out a PDF form on the website, which landed in a shared Gmail inbox. From there, a paralegal manually copied the information into Clio, drafted a conflict check email, waited for responses from three partners, then typed an engagement letter from a Word template — re-entering the same client details a third time.</p>
			<p style="margin-bottom:1rem;">The process took an average of 3.5 hours per new client and generated two to four data-entry errors per week. Conflict checks were occasionally skipped when the paralegal was out. Engagement letters sometimes sat unsent for three days because no one had flagged that a partner hadn't responded.</p>
			<p style="margin-bottom:1rem;">Document management was equally fragile. Pleadings, discovery responses, and client correspondence lived in a folder structure on a shared drive with no consistent naming convention. Associates spent an average of 22 minutes per matter per week just locating the right version of a document. One associate described the situation plainly: "We had notebooks doubling as to-do lists and a shared drive that nobody fully trusted."</p>
			<p style="margin-bottom:2rem;">The firm had looked at practice management add-ons before but found them expensive, rigid, and requiring more training than the small team could absorb. They wanted something that worked with the tools they already had — not a replacement system.</p>

			<h4 class="accent-subtitle">The Solution</h4>
			<p style="margin-bottom:1rem;">Eleoro began with a two-hour discovery call mapping every step of the intake process from web form to signed engagement letter. The existing tools — Google Workspace, Clio, and a shared Gmail inbox — stayed in place. The automation was built on top of them using n8n and OpenAI.</p>
			<p style="margin-bottom:1rem;"><strong>Workflow 1 — Automated intake and conflict check.</strong> When a prospect submits the intake form, an n8n workflow immediately creates a draft matter in Clio, populates all fields from the form data, and sends a structured conflict check request to all three partners simultaneously with a 48-hour response deadline. If no response is received, a reminder fires automatically.</p>
			<p style="margin-bottom:1rem;"><strong>Workflow 2 — Engagement letter drafting.</strong> OpenAI generates a first-draft engagement letter populated with the client's matter details, the correct fee structure pulled from a rate card Google Sheet, and the assigned attorney's signature block. The draft lands in the responsible attorney's Google Doc folder for review and one-click send.</p>
			<p style="margin-bottom:2rem;"><strong>Workflow 3 — Document naming and routing.</strong> New documents saved to the shared drive are automatically renamed to the firm's agreed convention and moved to the correct Clio matter folder. A weekly digest emails each attorney a list of documents added to their active matters that week.</p>

			<h4 class="accent-subtitle">Results — Measured Over 90 Days Post-Deployment</h4>
			<ul class="card-features" style="margin-bottom:2rem;">
				<li>Intake processing time dropped from 3.5 hours to 47 minutes per new client, measured by comparing Clio matter creation timestamps against engagement letter send timestamps before and after deployment</li>
				<li>18 billable hours recaptured per week across the firm, tracked via Clio's time reporting dashboard comparing the three months before and after go-live</li>
				<li>Zero conflict checks missed in 90 days, compared to an estimated two to three per quarter previously</li>
				<li>Document retrieval time reduced from an average of 22 minutes to under 4 minutes per matter per week, based on associate time logs</li>
				<li>Monthly overhead savings of approximately $3,400, calculated against paralegal hours previously spent on manual data entry and attorney time lost to document searches</li>
			</ul>

			<blockquote style="border-left:3px solid var(--color-accent); padding-left:1rem; margin:0 0 2rem 0; font-style:italic; opacity:0.9;">
