			<div style="display:grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(3,1fr); gap:1rem; margin-bottom:2rem;">
				<div class="service-card" style="text-align:center; padding:1rem;">
					<div style="font-size:2rem; font-weight:700; color:var(--color-accent);">71%</div>
					<div style="font-size:0.8rem; opacity:0.7; margin-top:0.25rem;">reduction in transaction coordination time</div>
				</div>
				<div class="service-card" style="text-align:center; padding:1rem;">
					<div style="font-size:2rem; font-weight:700; color:var(--color-accent);">11 hrs</div>
					<div style="font-size:0.8rem; opacity:0.7; margin-top:0.25rem;">saved per agent per month</div>
				</div>
				<div class="service-card" style="text-align:center; padding:1rem;">
					<div style="font-size:2rem; font-weight:700; color:var(--color-accent);">3x</div>
					<div style="font-size:0.8rem; opacity:0.7; margin-top:0.25rem;">increase in Google reviews</div>
				</div>
			</div>

			<blockquote style="border-left:3px solid var(--color-accent); padding-left:1rem; margin:0 0 2rem 0; font-style:italic; opacity:0.9;">
			"My agents were spending Friday afternoons doing paperwork. Now they spend Friday afternoons with clients. That's the whole story."
			<footer style="margin-top:0.5rem; font-style:normal; font-size:0.85rem; opacity:0.7;">— Hypothetical broker-owner, 34-agent real estate brokerage</footer>
			</blockquote>

			<h4 class="accent-subtitle">The Challenge</h4>
			<p style="margin-bottom:1rem;">Every closed transaction triggered the same cascade of manual work. The agent would notify the transaction coordinator by text or Slack. The coordinator would then manually update a Google Sheet, create a DocuSign envelope, send a checklist email to the client, log the commission split in a separate spreadsheet, notify the mortgage broker, schedule the closing reminder, and update the CRM — six different tools, none of them talking to each other.</p>
			<p style="margin-bottom:1rem;">On a good week with three closings, that was manageable. During busy months with eight to twelve closings, it broke down. Checklist emails went out late. Commission splits were logged with errors that took hours to untangle at month-end. Two clients in one quarter never received their post-closing follow-up survey.</p>
			<p style="margin-bottom:2rem;">The brokerage had one transaction coordinator handling all 34 agents. The coordinator was competent and organized — the process itself was the problem. "It wasn't a people issue," the broker-owner said. "It was a systems issue. We'd outgrown the way we set things up three years ago and just kept adding workarounds."</p>

			<h4 class="accent-subtitle">The Solution</h4>
			<p style="margin-bottom:1rem;">Eleoro spent the first week documenting every manual step in the transaction coordination process — not by asking what should happen, but by watching what actually happened across five real transactions. That observation uncovered three steps that weren't in any written procedure but happened consistently, and two written steps that no one actually followed.</p>
			<p style="margin-bottom:1rem;"><strong>Workflow 1 — Transaction trigger and checklist.</strong> When an agent marks a deal as under contract in the CRM, a Make workflow fires automatically: it creates a DocuSign envelope from the appropriate template, generates the client checklist email pre-populated with closing date and agent details, notifies the mortgage broker, and posts a Slack summary to the coordinator's channel — all within 90 seconds of the status change.</p>
			<p style="margin-bottom:1rem;"><strong>Workflow 2 — Commission and closing logistics.</strong> At closing, a single form submission triggers commission split calculation and logging, calendar invites for all parties, and a closing day reminder sequence to the client (48 hours out, morning of). The Google Sheet and CRM are updated from the same source — no double entry.</p>
			<p style="margin-bottom:2rem;"><strong>Workflow 3 — Post-closing follow-up sequence.</strong> Three days after closing, an OpenAI-drafted personal follow-up email goes out from the agent's address for review and one-click send. Fourteen days after closing, a Google review request goes out automatically. Thirty days after closing, a check-in message is queued for the agent to personalize.</p>

			<h4 class="accent-subtitle">Results — Measured Over 90 Days Post-Deployment</h4>
			<ul class="card-features" style="margin-bottom:2rem;">
				<li>Transaction coordination time per closing dropped from an average of 2.8 hours to 49 minutes, measured by coordinator time logs before and after deployment</li>
				<li>11 hours saved per agent per month, calculated across the full 34-agent team based on time previously spent on manual status updates, checklist follow-ups, and commission reconciliation</li>
				<li>Zero missed client follow-ups in 90 days — every post-closing sequence completed for every transaction</li>
				<li>Month-end commission reconciliation time dropped from 4.5 hours to 35 minutes, with error rate reduced to zero in the post-deployment period</li>
				<li>Google review volume increased 3x in the first 60 days as a direct result of the automated review request sequence</li>
			</ul>

			<blockquote style="border-left:3px solid var(--color-accent); padding-left:1rem; margin:0 0 2rem 0; font-style:italic; opacity:0.9;">
			"I was nervous about it, honestly. I thought we'd break something that was at least working most of the time. What surprised me is that the setup process itself showed us two things we were doing wrong that had nothing to do with automation. Eleoro caught them during the discovery week. That alone was worth it."
			<footer style="margin-top:0.5rem; font-style:normal; font-size:0.85rem; opacity:0.7;">— Hypothetical broker-owner, 34-agent real estate brokerage</footer>
			</blockquote>

